              "textDisplay": "+DrFrankenDeath When they did the comparison tests the atomic clocks were placed in special containers to protect them from outside influences. The tests have been repeated several times and  proves time dilation. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eGravity will affect our biological cells, and this has been demonstrated by astronauts and the goobers on the space station. Our cells are designed/evolved to function in Earth's gravity, so if we go into the weightless environment of space, or to a planet with weaker or stronger gravity, then our cells will function differently. For example, a weightless environment can result in more blood hanging around in the upper body which could affect how your brain works. They are still figuring out to what extent this will affect us. If you went into deep space the effect may be different again because you would be away from the gravitational field of the sun. It is theoretically possible that these physical changes could affect the aging process because it is changing the way the cells behave. However, time itself does not affect your biology. If you are up in space in a weaker gravitational field then time will go faster than if you are on Earth; and if you are travelling at a faster speed then time will go slower than on Earth. But it will still be the same time to you. Ten years will be ten years no matter what 'time zone' you are in, and you will be ten years older. Racer A was travelling at 10 mph so it took 1 hour to cover 10 miles. Racer B was doing 5 mph so it took him 2 hours to cover 10 miles. A was travelling faster than B so therefore time was going slower for him. But at that speed over that distance the time dilation would be negligible, almost immeasurable.
